<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="125" name="Alcohols, Phenols and Ethers">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Replacement of H by -OH group in an aliphatic hydrocarbon gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alcohol</option><option id="B">Phenol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contains R-OH structure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Replacement of H by -OH group in an aromatic hydrocarbon (directly on ring) gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Phenol</option><option id="B">Alcohol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contains Ar-OH structure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Substitution of H by alkoxy (-OR) or aryloxy (-OAr) group gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ethers</option><option id="B">Esters</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>General formula R-O-R or R-O-Ar.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Alcohols having two -OH groups are called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dihydric alcohols</option><option id="B">Monohydric</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Ethylene glycol.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Alcohols having three -OH groups are called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Trihydric alcohols</option><option id="B">Monohydric</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Glycerol.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Common name for 1,2,3-propanetriol is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Glycerol</option><option id="B">Glycol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Found in fats and oils.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phenols with two -OH groups are ____ phenols.</text>
            <option id="A">Dihydric</option><option id="B">Monohydric</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Catechol, Resorcinol, Quinol.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>C-O-H bond angle in alcohols is slightly ____ than tetrahedral angle.</text>
            <option id="A">Less (108.9°)</option><option id="B">Greater</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to repulsion between unshared electron pairs of oxygen.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In phenols, C-O bond length is shorter than in methanol due to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Partial double bond character (Resonance)</option><option id="B">sp3 hybridization</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Conjugation with aromatic ring.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acid catalyzed hydration of alkenes follows ____ rule.</text>
            <option id="A">Markovnikov's</option><option id="B">Saytzeff's</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Water adds to double bond in presence of acid.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hydroboration-oxidation of alkenes yields ____ product.</text>
            <option id="A">Anti-Markovnikov alcohol</option><option id="B">Markovnikov alcohol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Net addition of water across double bond.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reduction of aldehydes with H2/Ni gives ____ alcohols.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary (1°)</option><option id="B">Secondary (2°)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>R-CHO -&gt; R-CH2OH.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reduction of ketones with NaBH4 gives ____ alcohols.</text>
            <option id="A">Secondary (2°)</option><option id="B">Primary (1°)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>R-CO-R -&gt; R-CH(OH)-R.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of Grignard reagent with Formaldehyde (HCHO) gives ____ alcohol.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary (1°)</option><option id="B">Secondary</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Chain extension by one carbon.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of Grignard reagent with Ketones gives ____ alcohols.</text>
            <option id="A">Tertiary (3°)</option><option id="B">Secondary</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>R-CO-R + R'MgX -&gt; R2C(OH)R'.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aromatic primary amines + NaNO2/HCl followed by warm water gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Phenols</option><option id="B">Alcohols</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Via diazonium intermediate.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cumene is chemically ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Isopropylbenzene</option><option id="B">Ethylbenzene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Starting material for commercial phenol production.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Boiling points of alcohols/phenols are ____ than hydrocarbons of same mass.</text>
            <option id="A">Higher</option><option id="B">Lower</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to intermolecular hydrogen bonding.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Solubility of alcohols in water ____ with increase in alkyl chain length.</text>
            <option id="A">Decreases</option><option id="B">Increases</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hydrophobic part size increases.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Alcohols and phenols act as ____ acids.</text>
            <option id="A">Bronsted (Proton donors)</option><option id="B">Lewis bases only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reaction with active metals sets free H2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acid strength of alcohols: 1° &gt; 2° &gt; 3°. Correct? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electron launching groups (+I) decrease polarity of O-H bond.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phenols are ____ acidic than alcohols.</text>
            <option id="A">More</option><option id="B">Less</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Phenoxide ion is resonance stabilized.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Presence of Electron Withdrawing Groups (EWG) ____ the acidity of phenols.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Effective at ortho/para positions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Esterification: Alcohol + Carboxylic acid -&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ester + Water</option><option id="B">Ether</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Requires acid catalyst.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Dehydration of alcohols to alkenes follows reactivity order ____.</text>
            <option id="A">3° &gt; 2° &gt; 1°</option><option id="B">1° &gt; 2° &gt; 3°</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ease of carbocation formation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation of primary alcohols with PCC gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Aldehydes</option><option id="B">Carboxylic acids</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pyridinium chlorochromate is a mild reagent.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation of 1° alcohols with strong agents (KMnO4) gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carboxylic acids</option><option id="B">Aldehydes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Direct oxidation to acid.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Secondary alcohols oxidize to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ketones</option><option id="B">Aldehydes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Using CrO3 or other agents.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Tertiary alcohols under strong oxidation conditions give ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mixture of carboxylic acids (with cleavage)</option><option id="B">Ketones only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Resist oxidation unless C-C bonds break.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phenol + Br2 in CS2 (at low temp) gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">o and p-Bromophenol</option><option id="B">2,4,6-tribromophenol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Monobromination due to less polar solvent.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phenol + Bromine water gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2,4,6-tribromophenol (White ppt)</option><option id="B">o-bromophenol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highly activated ring gets substituted at all available sites.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Kolbe's reaction: Phenoxide + CO2 followed by H+ gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Salicylic acid (2-hydroxybenzoic acid)</option><option id="B">Aspirin</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard way to introduce -COOH in phenols.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reimer-Tiemann reaction: Phenol + CHCl3 + aq. NaOH followed by H+ gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Salicylaldehyde (2-hydroxybenzaldehyde)</option><option id="B">Salicylic acid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Introduction of -CHO group.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Dehydration of ethanol at 413 K with excess alcohol gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ethoxyethane (Diethyl ether)</option><option id="B">Ethene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>SN2 mechanism predominates at lower temp.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Dehydration of ethanol at 443 K gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ethene</option><option id="B">Diethyl ether</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Elimination favored at higher temp.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Williamson synthesis involves reaction of alkyl halide with ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sodium alkoxide</option><option id="B">Alcohol directly</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>SN2 attack of alkoxide on halide.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ethers have ____ dipole moment.</text>
            <option id="A">Low but significant (Polar)</option><option id="B">Zero</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Bent structure like water.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of HI with ethers yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alcohol and Alkyl iodide</option><option id="B">Alkane</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cleavage of C-O bond.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Methyl alcohol (Methanol) is also known as ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Wood spirit</option><option id="B">Grain alcohol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Traditionally prepared by destructive distillation of wood.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ethyl alcohol (Ethanol) is also known as ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Grain alcohol</option><option id="B">Wood spirit</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Common beverage alcohol.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Boiling point order: Alcohol &gt; Ether &gt; Hydrocarbon (for same mass)? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to H-bonding in alcohols.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phenol + Conc. HNO3 gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2,4,6-trinitrophenol (Picric acid)</option><option id="B">o/p-nitrophenol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Explosive compound, very acidic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phenol + Dilute HNO3 (at 298 K) gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">o and p-nitrophenol</option><option id="B">Picric acid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mixture can be separated by steam distillation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which is more steam volatile: o-nitrophenol or p-nitrophenol?</text>
            <option id="A">o-nitrophenol</option><option id="B">p-nitrophenol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>o-nitrophenol has intramolecular H-bonding.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acidity order: p-nitrophenol vs o-nitrophenol vs phenol? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">p-NP &gt; o-NP &gt; Phenol</option><option id="B">Phenol &gt; p-NP</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>NO2 is EWG, p-isomer is most acidic due to lack of intramolecular H-bond stabilizing OH.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Distinguishing 1°, 2° and 3° alcohols using Lucas test: 3° gives ____ turbidity.</text>
            <option id="A">Immediate</option><option id="B">After 5 mins</option><option id="C">Only on heating</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Rapid substitution due to stable 3° carbocation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Lucas test: 2° alcohols give turbidity in ____ mins.</text>
            <option id="A">5</option><option id="B">0</option><option id="C">60</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Slower than tertiary.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phenol + Zinc dust (heat) yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Benzene</option><option id="B">Cyclohexane</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reduction of phenol.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aspirin (Acetylsalicylic acid) is prepared by ____ of salicylic acid.</text>
            <option id="A">Acetylation (with acetic anhydride)</option><option id="B">Nitration</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Analgesic and antipyretic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation of phenol with Chromic acid gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">p-Benzoquinone</option><option id="B">Benzene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dark colored mixture in presence of air.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Glycerol + HI (limited) yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Allyl iodide</option><option id="B">Isopropyl iodide</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specific organic synthesis step.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Absolute alcohol is ____ pure ethanol.</text>
            <option id="A">100%</option><option id="B">95%</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used in laboratories and industry.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Rectified spirit contains ____ % ethanol.</text>
            <option id="A">95.5</option><option id="B">100</option><option id="C">50</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Azeotropic mixture.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Denatured alcohol (Methylated spirit) contains ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ethanol + Methanol / Pyridine</option><option id="B">Pure Ethanol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Made unfit for drinking.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Test for Phenol: Add FeCl3 solution, gives ____ color.</text>
            <option id="A">Violet / Blue / Green</option><option id="B">Red</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Complex formation with neutral FeCl3.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mechanism of dehydration of ethanol to ethene involves ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carbocation intermediate</option><option id="B">Carbanion</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Protonation -&gt; Water loss -&gt; Deprotonation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cleavage of C-O bond in ethers by HX follows ____ order of reactivity for HX.</text>
            <option id="A">HI &gt; HBr &gt; HCl</option><option id="B">HCl &gt; HBr &gt; HI</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Better nucleophilicity of iodide.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of Anisole (Methoxybenzene) with HI gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Phenol and Methyl iodide</option><option id="B">Iodobenzene and Methanol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Phenolic C-O bond is stronger due to resonance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nitration of Anisole gives majorly ____ product.</text>
            <option id="A">p-Nitroanisole</option><option id="B">o-Nitroanisole</option><option id="C">m-Nitroanisole</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>-OCH3 is o/p directing.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Friedel-Crafts Acetylation of Anisole gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">o/p-Methoxyacetophenone</option><option id="B">Toluene</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Using CH3COCl and AlCl3.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is used as a propellant and in aerosols?</text>
            <option id="A">Dimethyl ether</option><option id="B">Ethanol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Alternative to CFCs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Diethyl ether was widely used as a(n) ____.</text>
            <option id="A">General anaesthetic</option><option id="B">Fuel</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Replaced by safer halothanes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Highest acidity among cresols is shown by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">m-cresol (relative to others due to -I effect)</option><option id="B">Phenol (more acidic than cresols)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Alkyl groups are electron donating (+I), decrease acidity. Phenol &gt; m &gt; p &gt; o cresols.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acidity: p-nitrophenol vs p-methoxyphenol? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">p-NP &gt; p-MP</option><option id="B">p-MP &gt; p-NP</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>EWG (NO2) vs EDG (OCH3).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of alcohol with acid chlorides (RCOCl) in presence of Pyridine is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acylation</option><option id="B">Alkylation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pyridine neutralizes the HCl formed.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary, secondary and tertiary alcohols can be distinguished by ____ test.</text>
            <option id="A">Victor Meyer / Lucas</option><option id="B">Tollen's</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Victor Meyer: 1° (Blood red), 2° (Blue), 3° (Colorless).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Catalytic dehydrogenation of 1° alcohols with Cu at 573 K gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Aldehydes</option><option id="B">Alkenes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>RCH2OH -&gt; RCHO + H2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Catalytic dehydrogenation of 2° alcohols with Cu at 573 K gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ketones</option><option id="B">Aldehydes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>R2CHOH -&gt; R2CO + H2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Catalytic treatment of 3° alcohols with Cu at 573 K gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alkenes (Dehydration)</option><option id="B">Ketones</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Tertiary alcohols resist dehydrogenation, undergo dehydration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Azeotropic mixture of ethanol and water cannot be separated by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Simple distillation</option><option id="B">Fractional distillation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Composition remains same in liquid and vapor.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Schotten-Baumann reaction involves benzoylation of alcohol with ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Benzoyl chloride [C6H5COCl]</option><option id="B">Benzaldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>In presence of NaOH (aq).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Libermann's Nitroso reaction is used for identifying ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Phenols</option><option id="B">Alcohols</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Characteristic color changes with NaNO2/H2SO4 and then water/NaOH.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phthalic anhydride + Phenol (with conc. H2SO4) gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Phenolphthalein (Indicator)</option><option id="B">Aspirin</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used in acid-base titrations.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ethers are used as ____ in Grignard reagents and in industry.</text>
            <option id="A">Inert solvents</option><option id="B">Reactants</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Do not react with common reagents at normal temp.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ethers form peroxides on standing in air. This is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dangerous / Explosive</option><option id="B">Beneficial</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Auto-oxidation by O2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Test for peroxides in ether: add KI and starch. Peroxides liberate ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Iodine (Blue color)</option><option id="B">O2</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Oxidizes I- to I2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ziesel's method is used for estimation of ____ groups.</text>
            <option id="A">Alkoxy (like -OCH3)</option><option id="B">Hydroxy</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Using HI to form RI.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phenol + NaNO2 + H2SO4 -&gt; Deep green color. This is ____ reaction.</text>
            <option id="A">Libermann</option><option id="B">Kolbe</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Detailed name for the test.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Conversion of Glycerol to Glycerol trinitrate gives ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nitro-glycerine (Explosive)</option><option id="B">Fuel</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used in dynamite.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Methanol + CO -&gt; Acetic acid is ____ process.</text>
            <option id="A">Monsanto</option><option id="B">Haber</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Carbonylation reaction.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following describes the behavior of ortho-nitrophenol in steam distillation?</text>
            <option id="A">Steam volatile due to intramolecular H-bonding</option><option id="B">Non-volatile due to intermolecular H-bonding</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Chelation reduces the tendency to form H-bonds with water.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following describes the behavior of para-nitrophenol in steam distillation?</text>
            <option id="A">Non-volatile due to intermolecular H-bonding</option><option id="B">Steam volatile</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Strong association with other molecules.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acidity order: o-nitrophenol vs p-nitrophenol vs m-nitrophenol? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">p-NP &gt; o-NP &gt; m-NP</option><option id="B">m-NP &gt; p-NP</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>NO2 is EWG; m-position lacks resonance (-M) effect.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Formation of salicylic acid from phenol using CCl4 and NaOH is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Modified Reimer-Tiemann</option><option id="B">Kolbe's</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Using CCl4 instead of CHCl3 gives acid directly.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which reagent is used to convert phenol to benzene? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zinc dust (heat)</option><option id="B">NaOH</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Simple reduction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reaction of glycerol with excess of HI yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2-Iodopropane (Isopropyl iodide)</option><option id="B">Allyl iodide</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Complete reduction follows initial substitution.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following has the highest acidity?</text>
            <option id="A">2,4,6-trinitrophenol (Picric acid)</option><option id="B">Phenol</option><option id="C">m-nitrophenol</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Strongly EWG groups at all o/p positions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Intermediate in Reimer-Tiemann reaction is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dichlorocarbene (:CCl2)</option><option id="B">Carbocation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electrophilic species attacking the phenoxide.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Action of HI on (CH3)3C-O-CH3 yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(CH3)3C-I and CH3-OH</option><option id="B">(CH3)3C-OH and CH3-I</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proceeds via SN1 due to tertiary group, forming stable carbocation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Action of HI on CH3-CH2-O-CH3 yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">CH3-I and CH3-CH2-OH</option><option id="B">CH3-OH and CH3-CH2-I</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proceeds via SN2, I- attacks the smaller alkyl group.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phenol + Na2Cr2O7/H2SO4 yields ____.</text>
